# World of Printers

> Have you ever wanted a single pane of glass to oversee all of your industrial printers? Yeah, me too.  

```diagram

```

> Wait, no no. I wasn't talking about that kind of single pane. I meant something like this.

```diagram

```

> That's better, but I don't just want to stare at them.  I'm not building a printer NOC. I am running a business that utilizes printers to move material.  If material doesn't move then we're not making money.  I need my printers to be available and the print quality consistent.

```diagram

```

> Ok, so where do we start?  How do we ensure that our equipment is serving our business?

---

Every make has some sort of networked interface to fulfill its duty as a printer and provide data points about its operating status and parameters.

|   |   |
|---|---|
| [Zebra Programming Guide](https://www.zebra.com/content/dam/zebra/manuals/printers/common/programming/zpl-zbi2-pm-en.pdf) | This guide is the unabridged, alphabetical reference of programming commands supported in the firmware. This includes all ZPL commands and SGD commands. |
| [SATO API](https://www.sato-global.com/files/Integration_Options/SATO_Printer_API/UM_SATOPrinterAPI_EN.pdf) | Software developers can use this API to send printer commands to the printer as well as to receive a response from the printer if there is any.  |
| [Printronix PXML](https://printronix.com/wp-content/uploads/manuals/PTX_PRM_PXML_253343B.pdf) | This manual describes a communication model for remotely managing Printronix printers. It is for application developers to implement custom printer management schemes. |
| [Honeywell Mobility SDK](https://sps.honeywell.com/us/en/software/productivity/development-tools/mobility-sdk-windows) | Build innovative applications for Honeywell computers, printers, and RFID that incorporate the latest mobile, communication and data collection technologies. |

We're in luck.  It seems that every printer make is capable of communicating over a TCP/IP network.  

```diagram

```

We'll focus on a Zebra implemenation because it is most straight forward exchange of ASCII characters over a TCP/IP socket. 

---

Two basic things we want to know about our printer is whether it's online and its health.  'Online' could mean a lot of things, but in the context of the printer's ability to serve print requests we'll settle for a successful response to a PING request over the network.

```diagram

```

An [Event](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__578514fe-2c65-4428-a2a6-77dd0059b660) category data item of [AVAILABILITY](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__efa904df-e614-4dde-81d4-3d9d41ea5596) type will represent our ability to communicate with the printer.  An event contains a finite number of states.

```diagram

```

```xml
<!-- info model -->
<DataItem category="EVENT" id="avail" type="AVAILABILITY"/>
```

Next we need the general health of the printer. Here is an example of a host status command response. The printer is indeed in an error state.

![printer1.png](/world_of_printers/printer1.png)

To be more precise, the printer is in an error state, head is open, and it is paused.

![printer2.png](/world_of_printers/printer2.png)

A [Condition](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__b5a9fb61-fd07-4e9d-a7a5-83ead254c35d) category data item of [SYSTEM](https://model.mtconnect.org/#Architecture__20946092-12aa-4baa-84dd-d38ed684782f) type will represent the overall health of the printer.

```xml
<!-- info model -->
<DataItem category="CONDITION" id="system_cond" type="SYSTEM"/>
```
